Since Jane visits the bookstore every month, we can find the date of her visit one year ago by subtracting one year from today's date and checking which visit that would be. Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\text{(D) }03/13/2009}$.

Today is the palindrome day of 2020, because the MMDDYYYY format of the date is the same backwards as forwards. What is the date a month ago in MM/DD/YYYY?
Options:
(A) 01/01/2020
(B) 01/02/2020
(C) 10/02/2019
(D) 11/05/2019
(E) 01/02/1931
(F) 01/03/2020
column3: Since today's date is a palindrome, it must be in the form $ABCCBACBA$, where $A$, $B$, and $C$ are digits (note that $A$ cannot be zero). We know that $C$ must be 2 since the date is in January. Then $A$ and $B$ must be 0, 1, or 2. If $B$ were 2, then the date would be February 22, which is invalid since February only has 29 days in a leap year, and 2020 is a leap year. Therefore, $B$ is either 0 or 1.  Now, we can consider the date a month ago. If $B$ is 0, then the date would be 1220220, which is not a valid date. Therefore, $B$ must be 1, and the date would be 1212120. This corresponds to $\boxed{\textbf{(D) }11/05/2019}$.

Yesterday was 12/31/1929. Today could not be 12/32/1929 because December has only 31 days. What is the date one year ago from today in MM/DD/YYYY?
Options:
(A) 01/01/1898
(B) 01/01/1994
(C) 08/01/1929
(D) 01/08/1929
(E) 01/01/1891
(F) 01/01/1929
column3: One year ago from today is the same date, but in the previous year. Since today is not a leap year, we cannot just subtract 1 from the year. Instead, we have to keep in mind that the year changed, and that February has fewer days in non-leap years. December 31, 1929 was a Tuesday, so December 31, 1930 was a Wednesday.   Thus, working backwards, we know that the previous year was 1929. January 31, 1929 was a Thursday. Since 1929 was not a leap year, February had 28 days, so February 28, 1929 was a Thursday. March 31, April 30, and May 31 all fell on different weekdays as well, and June 30, 1929 was a Sunday. For all these months, we have to work forwards, since we are going backwards from December 31, 1930.   For instance: April 30, 1929 (a Wednesday) was 214 days before December 31. Since there are 7 days in a week, we know that the weekday 214 days later will be the same as the weekday 6 days later. Going forward from April 30, we get May 1 (a Thursday), June 1 (a Saturday), July 1 (a Monday), August 1 (a Thursday), September 1 (a Sunday), October 1 (a Tuesday), November 1 (a Friday), and finally December 1 (a Sunday). Since December 1, 1929 is 30 days behind December 31, 1929, we know that December 1, 1929 was a Sunday. We can also see that the same pattern holds for the other months:   | Month | Date | Weekday | |-------|------|---------| | Jan   | 31   | Thurs   | | Feb   | 28   | Thurs   | | Mar   | 31   | Sun     | | Apr   | 30   | Tues    | | May   | 31   | Fri     | | Jun   | 30   | Sun     | | Jul   | 31   | Wed     | | Aug   | 31   | Sat     | | Sep   | 30   | Mon     | | Oct   | 31   | Thu     | | Nov   | 30   | Sat     | | Dec   | 1    | Sun     |  Therefore, one year ago from today was 01/01/1929, which is option $\boxed{\textbf{(F)}}$.

column3: If Jane and John got married on Jan 2, 1958, then their first anniversary was on Jan 2, 1959, their second anniversary was on Jan 2, 1960, their third anniversary was on Jan 2, 1961, and their fourth anniversary was on Jan 2, 1962. Since it is their 5-year anniversary today (Jan 2, 1963), one year ago from today would be Jan 2, 1962. Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{\textbf{(B)}\ 01/02/1960}$.

Jane was born on the last day of Feburary in 2000. Today is her 16-year-old birthday. What is the date a month ago in MM/DD/YYYY?
Options:
(A) 05/04/2016
(B) 07/29/2015
(C) 02/02/2016
(D) 11/08/2015
(E) 01/30/2016
(F) 01/29/2016
column3: Since 2000 is a leap year, February has 29 days. Jane's birthday this year would be on February 29, 2016, and her 16-year-old birthday would be on February 28 (since there is no February 29th on a non-leap year). Therefore, a month ago would be January 28, 2016. The answer is $\boxed{\text{(F) } 01/29/2016}$.
